## 11. Gotchas & Lessons Learned <a name="gotchas"></a>

### 🚨 Gotcha #1: xterm.js Addon Imports Must Be Dynamic

**Problem:** Static imports of xterm.js and its addons crash during Astro's build step because they reference `window` and `document`.

**Before (broken):**
```tsx
// ❌ This crashes during `npm run build`
import { Terminal } from 'xterm';
import { FitAddon } from '@xterm/addon-fit';
import 'xterm/css/xterm.css';

export default function Terminal() {
  // ...
}
```

**After (working):**
```tsx
// ✅ Dynamic imports inside useEffect — only runs in browser
export default function Terminal() {
  useEffect(() => {
    async function init() {
      const { Terminal } = await import('xterm');
      const { FitAddon } = await import('@xterm/addon-fit');
      await import('xterm/css/xterm.css');

      // Now safe to use Terminal, FitAddon
    }
    init();
  }, []);
}
```

And you **must** use `client:only="react"` in the Astro template — not `client:load`. The latter tries to SSR the component first, which still crashes.

### 🚨 Gotcha #2: CRT Effects Need Careful Z-Index Management

**Problem:** CRT scanlines and flicker effects overlay the terminal. If z-index isn't managed carefully:
- Scanlines block mouse clicks on the terminal
- Text selection doesn't work
- Cursor appears behind the overlay

**Solution — Layering order:**

```css
.screen-content {
  position: relative;
  z-index: var(--z-base);  /* 0 — Terminal content */
}

.crt-overlay {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  z-index: var(--z-scanlines);  /* 200 — Above content */
  pointer-events: none;  /* ⚠️ CRITICAL: Allow clicks to pass through */
}

.scanlines {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  background: repeating-linear-gradient(
    0deg,
    rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15) 0px,
    rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15) 1px,
    transparent 1px,
    transparent 3px
  );
  pointer-events: none;
}

.crt-flicker {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  background: rgba(0, 255, 65, 0.02);
  animation: flicker 0.1s infinite alternate;
  pointer-events: none;
}

@keyframes flicker {
  from { opacity: 0.95; }
  to { opacity: 1.0; }
}
```

> **The key rule:** Any overlay element that's purely visual MUST have `pointer-events: none`. Without it, users can't interact with the terminal below.

### 🚨 Gotcha #3: Astro Scoped Styles Don't Reach React Islands

**Problem:** Styles defined in `<style>` tags in `.astro` files are scoped. They won't apply to children rendered by React islands.

**Solution:** Use `:global()` or import CSS from the React component:

```astro
<style>
  /* This WON'T style the Terminal component's internals */
  .terminal-container { color: green; }

  /* This WILL */
  :global(.terminal-container) { color: green; }
</style>
```

Or better — use a separate CSS file imported in the React component:
```tsx
// Terminal.tsx
import '../styles/terminal.css';  // Imported in the component itself
```

### 🚨 Gotcha #4: Font Loading Delays

**Problem:** Custom fonts (IBM Plex Mono) take time to load. The terminal briefly shows in the fallback font, then shifts when the custom font loads (FOUT — Flash of Unstyled Text).

**Solution:** Preload the font:
```html
<head>
  <link rel="preload" href="/fonts/IBMPlexMono-Regular.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin />
  <link rel="preload" href="/fonts/IBMPlexMono-Bold.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin />
</head>
```

Or use `font-display: swap` in your `@font-face`:
```css
@font-face {
  font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono';
  src: url('/fonts/IBMPlexMono-Regular.woff2') format('woff2');
  font-weight: 400;
  font-display: swap;
}
```

